posts.subject: Satire site Babylon Bee considers legal action against New York Times
posts.body:
There is no place on earth to escape PC people, and they are all a humorous lot.

Subject: 	Satire site Babylon Bee considers legal action against New York Times for trying to frame it as “misinformation” spreader
Date: 	Fri, 23 Apr 2021 16:40:49 +0000
From: 	Arnold Zafra


Babylon Bee, the popular satirical website, is considering legal action against the New York Times after the outlet labeled its content as “misinformation.”

Babylon Bee CEO, Seth Dillon said that their website has been constantly targeted by mainstream media outlets and personalities.

According to Dillon, these people claim that Babylon Bee is not a satire website but a disinformation site where fake news is posted to mislead people. This, Dillon alleges, is to eventually get the outlet deplatformed by Big Tech.

Framing something as “misinformation” has been a powerful technique to get people and content deplatformed in recent times.

One such media outlets is of course the New York Times which recently put out a report saying that Babylon Bee sometimes trafficked misinformation under the guise of satire.

Dillon said that similar claims were made by some CNN presenters.

“They put this stuff out there and if they can get it to stick, then then we have no platform remaining. There’s not going to be anybody who wants to host our stuff. … It’s an effort to try and cancel us,” Dillon told Fox.

Dillon also said that while the New York Times has been condemning them for being spreader of misinformation, it is ironic the NYT is trafficking misinformation about the satire website.

“We are contemplating and discussing with our counsel what the next move should be. Should we sue them or not. And that’s an open question,” he said. “We’re exploring our options.”

posts.subject: Claymore thread
posts.body:
Home built equivalents for the classic Claymore . Ingenious use of common materials is encouraged.

The M18A1 Claymore is a directional anti-personnel mine developed for the United States Armed Forces. Its inventor, Norman MacLeod, named the mine after a large medieval Scottish sword. Unlike a conventional land mine, the Claymore is command-detonated and directional, meaning it is fired by remote-control and shoots a pattern of metal balls into the kill zone like a shotgun. The Claymore can also be victim-activated by booby-trapping it with a tripwire firing system for use in area denial operations.

The Claymore fires steel balls out to about 100 m (110 yd) within a 60° arc in front of the device. It is used primarily in ambushes and as an anti-infiltration device against enemy infantry. It is also used against unarmored vehicles.

posts.subject: Ideas which might be testworthy thread
posts.body:
"Trail Boss" is an Australian powder which is imported for Cowboy Action Competition events.

Less known are it's abilities to provide "reduced load" shooting or "subsonic load shooting". And the envelope for this kind of utilization really isn't yet established.

I've used the .45ACP Trail Boss @ 4.5 gr with plated 230gr round nose quite a bit. It's a very soft shooter and sounds like a deep throated air rifle.

When you hand such loads to "normies" or women, prepare yourself for astonishment when they neatly punch out the bulls eye. Very accurate.

Have never tried these loads in carbines. Was always concerned the bullets would stick in those long barrels. But with current events in mind - this is something I just must try.

Reasoning? Even pistol caliber carbines have a limited fire rate given recoil. Soft shooters like this might allow one to slow down Orcs for later disposal via a scoped bolt rifle. Modern pistol caliber carbines now offer voluminous magazines. Emptying a few of those might be highly effective for slowing down a crisis.

A standard 230gr 45ACP bullet is good for 14in penetration at common loading levels.  Would expect the Trail Boss variant to be good for at least 8-10". 

While single 45ACP hits have achieved "lights out"....a more typical average is 3 hits. I would expect that this Trail Boss load achieves that kill level with the same number of hits.

Again, the idea is to get all the bullets distributed QUICKLY. Not unlike a stepwise buckshot distribution.

Orcs on the ground are easier to kill.

>>47a8300f-b249-4cfe-8db2-ce04b05d58b9
Probably not a reliable source, but I would believe they couldn't make up these stories of infection?

In any case, such infections might be the only thing standing between YOU and fighting an Orc again. If safe delivery can be mastered - it would be a potent weapon.

posts.body:

Subject: 	France draws up new internet surveillance anti-terrorist bill
Date: 	Thu, 29 Apr 2021 12:14:39 +0000
From: 	Dan Frieth


In an effort to strengthen its counter-terrorism laws, France is considering a bill that would allow the monitoring of websites. This new development is in response to a wave of terror attacks by Islamic extremists in recent years; the most recent was last Friday.

During a cabinet meeting on Wednesday, a draft legislation legalizing the use of algorithms to surveil activity on jihadist websites was presented to President Emanuel Macron. The bill would strengthen the counterterrorism law introduced in 2017, following a terror attack in Paris by Islamist gunmen and suicide bombers two years earlier.

The 2017 law, which was to be reviewed after 4 years, gave intelligence agencies the authority to use algorithms to monitor messaging services. It also bolstered surveillance by police, to include measures such as “home visits” to persons suspected of terrorism.

The new bill would make the existing measures permanent, and extend the use of surveillance algorithms to websites.

“The last nine attacks on French soil were committed by individuals who were unknown to the security services, who were not on a watchlist and were not suspected of being radicalized,” Interior Minister Gerald Darmanin told France Inter radio.

“That should cause us to ask questions about the intelligence methods we’re using,” Darmanin continued. “Terrorists have changed the methods of communication. We continue to be blind, monitoring phone lines that nobody uses any more.”

For example, last Friday’s attack was conducted by a Tunisian immigrant after watching videos praising acts of jihad. He killed someone who worked for the police in a commuter town in Paris.

The post France draws up new internet surveillance anti-terrorist bill appeared first on Reclaim The Net.
